    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faq" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on Critical Skills permit?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">After 12 months, you can change employers without a new permit application—just notify immigration. Before 12 months, changing requires a new permit application. Critical Skills holders have more flexibility than General Employment permit holders.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get permanent residence?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Critical Skills: Apply for Stamp 4 after 2 years of employment. General Employment: Apply after 5 years. Stamp 4 gives you freedom to work for any employer without permit. After 5 years on Stamp 4, you can apply for citizenship.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my spouse work?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Spouses of Critical Skills permit holders can apply for Stamp 1G, which allows them to work without needing their own employment permit. This is a significant advantage. General Employment permit spouse options are more limited.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I qualify for Medical Card?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Medical Cards are means-tested. Most working professionals earning above ~€184/week (single) don't qualify. You might qualify for GP Visit Card if income is below certain thresholds. Most expats on professional salaries need private insurance.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is Lifetime Community Rating?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">If you're over 34 when you first take out private health insurance in Ireland, you pay a loading of 2% per year of age over 34, up to age 69. Example: entering at 44 means 20% higher premiums for life. Getting insurance early saves money long-term.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I apply for Irish citizenship?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">After 5 years of residence (with at least 1 year continuous before application), you can apply for citizenship by naturalization. Total reckonable residence of 5 of the last 9 years required. Having Stamp 4 counts toward this. Processing takes 12-24 months.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        Ireland offers an excellent combination for English-speaking professionals: EU membership, strong job market (especially tech), and a relatively fast path to permanent residence through the Critical Skills route. The 2-year pathway to Stamp 4 is one of Europe's quickest PR routes.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        Healthcare requires careful planning. Unlike the UK's NHS, Irish public healthcare charges fees and has long wait times. Private insurance is standard among professionals and often provided by employers. The 20% tax relief makes coverage more affordable than headline prices suggest. If you're over 34, enter the insurance market early to avoid Lifetime Community Rating loadings.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        The biggest challenge isn't the permit process—it's housing. Dublin's rental market is extremely competitive, with limited supply and high prices. Budget significantly more than you expect, and consider living outside the city center or in commuter towns initially.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-2">Bottom Line</h3>
        <p class="text-primary-800">Ireland is ideal for tech professionals, healthcare workers, and others in critical skills occupations who want EU access with English as the working language. Private health insurance is essential—negotiate it as part of your package or purchase individually. The 2-year path to Stamp 4 is the real prize, offering freedom from permit restrictions and a clear route to citizenship.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

